    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Mobile Development</h2>
    <h4 class="text-center mb-4">The essential skills every mobile developer must have.</h4>
    <p>These days there are a large set of tools available for building mobile apps. But these tools fall into two categories: native and cross-platform tools.</p>
    <p>With native tools, you can build apps for a specific platform (e.g., iOS or Android). Each platform has its own programming languages and tools. So to target multiple platforms, you have to learn many tools and write code in different languages.</p>
    <p>Alternatively, you can use a cross-platform solution (e.g., React Native or Flutter) to build apps for multiple platforms using a single codebase.</p>

    <h5>JavaScript</h5>
    <p>JavaScript is the programming language of the web and is widely used in mobile app development, especially with cross-platform frameworks like React Native.</p>
    <p>Steps to follow:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Learn basic JavaScript syntax, data types, and control structures.</li>
        <li>Explore advanced topics like closures, promises, and asynchronous programming.</li>
        <li>Learn TypeScript, a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing and other features.</li>
    </ul>
    <h5>Resources:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript" target="_blank">MDN Web Docs: JavaScript</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/" target="_blank">TypeScript Documentation</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h5>React</h5>
    <p>React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces, commonly used for building cross-platform mobile apps with React Native.</p>
    <p>Steps to follow:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Learn React basics, including JSX syntax, components, and props.</li>
        <li>Explore advanced React concepts like state management, hooks, and context API.</li>
    </ul>
    <h5>Resources:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://reactjs.org/docs/getting-started.html" target="_blank">React Documentation</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h5>React Native</h5>
    <p>React Native is a popular cross-platform framework for building mobile apps using JavaScript and React. It allows you to write code once and deploy it on both iOS and Android platforms.</p>
    <p>Steps to follow:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Learn React Native fundamentals, including components, navigation, and styling.</li>
        <li>Explore advanced topics like native module integration, performance optimization, and debugging.</li>
    </ul>
    <h5>Resources:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://reactnative.dev/docs/getting-started" target="_blank">React Native Documentation</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Version Control and Collaboration</h5>
    <p>Version control is like a time machine for software engineers. It allows you to go back in time and see the exact state of your code at any point. This is incredibly important because it means you can easily track changes, fix bugs, and collaborate with others without the fear of losing or messing up your code.</p>
